 143: 	"""
 144: 	Constructs a feature matrix where the paths extracted in previous
 145: 	step (input here) act as features. A value in the matrix corresponding 
 146: 	to a training instance (s, p, o) is the probability of arriving at 
 147: 	node o by a random walk starting at node s and a specific path (feature).
 148: 
 149: 	There are exact and approximate approaches to compute this. Exact approach 
 150: 	is costly however: complexity is proportional to the average per-edge-label 
 151: 	(or per-relation) out-degree to the power of the path length per source node 
 152: 	per path. Hence, we compute this probability using the approximate method of 
 153: 	rejection sampling. It works as follows: a number of random walks are performed
 154: 	starting at node 's', each attempting to follow the path (feature). If a 
 155: 	node is reached where it is no longer possible to follow the path, the 
 156: 	random walk is restarted. The fraction of walks that land in node 'o' 
 157: 	represents the probability.
 158: 
 159: 	Parameters:
 160: 	-----------

 162: 		Knowledge Graph.

 167: 		belonging to the same relation/predicate p.
 168: 	maxwalks: int
